# Discord Channel Analysis: üí¨-discussion

## 1. Summary

This chat segment contains minimal technical discussion, being dominated by off-topic casual conversation. The few technical elements include:

**Korean Exchange Delisting**: Multiple users discussed ai16z/elizaOS delisting from Korean exchanges (Bithumb, Coinone, Korbit). Skullcross provided detailed context that DAXA (Korean exchange regulatory body) terminated support due to transparency issues with the migration process. The delisting is confirmed for February 9-12, 2026, with Korean market access effectively closed.

**Migration Issues**: XXI_Rapax reported problems migrating pre-November ai16z tokens, showing 0 eligible tokens despite holding 10. Users were directed to migration support channels. Another user (Dabel) had issues with tokens in Raydium LP showing "max amount reached" error.

**Token Utility Discussion**: stoikol questioned the lack of utility for elizaOS token, asking why it's not used for payments or gas fees within the ecosystem. FoRever_BIG clarified it wasn't built as a gas fee token. degenwtf criticized the team for not explaining token utility or use cases clearly.

**Jeju Platform**: elizafan222 shared a GitHub commit for "bazaar" - sb clarified this is the decentralized marketplace/appstore for agents running on Jeju platform.

**Community Event**: Kenk announced a Twitter Space with Solana Foundation, PayAI, and Quantu on January 13th at 7pm UTC discussing 8004 standard and Eliza Cloud integration.

The majority of the 400+ messages were unrelated casual conversation about TV shows, gaming (Runescape, GTA), personal anecdotes, and philosophical discussions.

(asked by Majid) A: Due to transparency issues - ai16z failed to disclose material information appropriately and had deficiencies in migration procedure transparency. DAXA determined these issues weren't resolved with elizaOS rebrand. (answered by Skullcross, Ï£ºÎãà)

# Discord Channel Analysis: üí¨-coders

## 1. Summary

The channel discussion centered on several key technical areas related to Eliza development and ecosystem integration.

**Context Graphs and Data Infrastructure**: jin shared Foundation Capital's article on context graphs as a trillion-dollar AI opportunity, noting that Eliza has a strong data foundation to build context graphs. This sparked discussion about data collection strategies.

**Eliza Cloud Deployment**: Technical questions emerged about deploying on ElizaCloud via containers, specifically whether to use Pglite or PostgreSQL. cjft confirmed either option works. ElizaBAO reported issues with the cloud app creator showing "Operation failed" errors, though cjft confirmed it was functioning. The platform received updates including a new billing page for credit top-ups.

**Plugin Interoperability Experiment**: jin proposed a collaboration to convert ElizaOS plugins into skills and test interoperability across different agent tools, specifically targeting Discord and blockchain plugins as test cases.

**Data Collection for AI Training**: DorianD proposed an Eliza Phone App concept for users to share data in exchange for reputation points and LLM training contributions. The discussion evolved into exploring Jeju (a layer2 focused on decentralized AI apps) integration and innovative data collection methods including mocap suits for capturing movement data from activities like fly-fishing or food service work. The concept involved paying people IOUs for data collection and creating royalty systems where data providers earn from inference when androids use their captured skills.

**Twitter/X Integration**: Discostu asked about X API requirements and costs ($200/month) versus scraping alternatives. Psyxh later asked if Twitter API is required to run a Twitter agent.

**8004 Standard**: Kenk announced a space with Solana Foundation discussing the 8004 standard and its utilization in Eliza Cloud. jin shared related content from Stanford cryptographer Dan Boneh.

**Community Projects**: Several Eliza-based projects were shared including BountyBoard and KamiyoAI protocol, which appeared to use ElizaOS plugins.

## 2. FAQ

Q: For deploying in Elizacloud via containers should i use Pglite or PostgresSQL? (asked by Omid Sa) A: Either will work (answered by cjft)

Q: If i want to use eliza for X, helping me to find stuff on x i need to pay for x API or eliza have something to help/scrap this without needing to pay 200$ month? (asked by Discostu) A: Unanswered

Q: Do you need twitter api to use eliza to run a twitter agent? (asked by Psyxh) A: Unanswered

Q: Elizacloud app creator is it function? i try to create. is Operation failed (asked by ElizaBAO) A: Should be im using it now, early feature (answered by cjft)

## 3. Help Interactions

# Discord Chat Analysis - core-devs Channel

## 1. Summary

The discussion centered on three major technical initiatives:

**AI Agent Data Foundation & Integration**: jin highlighted the team's strong data foundation for AI agents, noting that daily/weekly/monthly insights from agentic workflows are high quality but need integration into last-mile applications (agents, webhooks, apps). This represents a key architectural gap between data generation and practical application.

**Plugin-to-Skills Conversion Experiment**: jin proposed converting elizaos plugins into interoperable skills, specifically targeting Discord and blockchain plugins. R0am volunteered to collaborate, explaining the technical approach: skills would be structured as folders containing .md instructions and deterministic scripts in any language. The main challenge identified was getting Claude to use skills implicitly rather than explicitly, which R0am claims to have solved using hooks. Stan confirmed working on similar implementation.

**Skill Workflow Orchestration**: Agent Joshua described challenges with multi-step skill workflows, providing a concrete example: specialized skill collects user information ‚Üí PDF skill fills form ‚Üí filesystem skill stores files with summarization ‚Üí PDF skill displays result. The difficulty lies in ensuring skills can call back and forth effectively. R0am referenced successful subagent linking implementations that could apply to skills.

**Eliza 2.0 Proposal**: shaw proposed a radical redesign - multi-language runtime (TypeScript, Rust, Python) with FFI plugin interoperability, removing API/server/CLI/projects in favor of a Claude-friendly documented runtime with unified abstractions. shaw confirmed having already ported it with a branch available.

Additional context: Discussion of inference market profitability challenges, minimax m2's interleaved thinking for long-running tasks, and upcoming elizaos leaderboard updates.

## 2. FAQ

Q: Has anyone played coding with minimax m2 here? (asked by R0am | tip.md) A: Unanswered

Q: What does converting elizaos plugins into skills involve technically? (asked by jin) A: A folder with .md instructions and tools in scripts (whatever language) to make them deterministic. The real challenge is getting Claude to use skills without saying explicitly, but there's a solution using hooks. (answered by R0am | tip.md)

Q: How do you ensure skills can be called back and forth in workflows? (asked by Agent Joshua ‚Ç± | TEE) A: There was a successful implementation of linking subagents that should work for skills, referenced via Reddit post. (answered by R0am | tip.md)
